# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: propane
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] 1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane is a non-flammable gas used primarily as a "high-temperature" refrigerant for domestic refrigeration and automobile air conditioners.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] These devices began using 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane in the early 1990s as a replacement for the more environmentally harmful R-12.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Retrofit kits are available to convert units that were originally R-12-equipped.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Other common uses include plastic foam blowing, as a cleaning solvent, a propellant for the delivery of pharmaceuticals (e.g., inhaler canisters such as for bronchodilators), wine cork removers, gas dusters ("canned air"), and in air driers for removing the moisture from compressed air.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] 1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane has also been used to cool computers in some overclocking attempts.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It is the refrigerant used in plumbing pipe freeze kits.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It is also commonly used as a propellant for airsoft airguns.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] The gas is often mixed with a silicone-based lubricant.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] 1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane is also being considered as an organic solvent, both as a liquid and a supercritical fluid.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It is used in the resistive plate chamber particle detectors in the Large Hadron Collider.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It is also used for other types of particle detectors, e.g. some cryogenic particle detectors.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It can be used as an alternative to sulfur hexafluoride in magnesium smelting as a shielding gas.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] 1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane was introduced in the early 1990s as a replacement for dichlorodifluoromethane (R-12), which has massive ozone depleting properties.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Even though 1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane has insignificant ozone depletion potential (ozone layer) and negligible acidification potential (acid rain), it has a 100-year global warming potential (GWP) of 1430 and an approximate atmospheric lifetime of 14 years.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Its concentration in the atmosphere and contribution to radiative forcing have been growing since its introduction.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Thus it was included in the IPCC list of greenhouse gases.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] R-134a began being phased out from use in the European Union, starting in the mid 2010s, by a directive of 2006, recommending the replacement of gases in air conditioning systems with a GWP above 100.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane is subject to use restrictions in the US and other countries as well.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] The Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) has proposed that it be best replaced by a new fluorochemical refrigerant HFO-1234yf (CF3CF=CH2) in automobile air-conditioning systems.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] As of model year 2021, newly manufactured light-duty vehicles in the United States no longer use R-134a.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] California may also prohibit the sale of canned R-134a to individuals to avoid non-professional recharge of air conditioners.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] A ban had been in place in Wisconsin since October 1994 under ATCP 136 prohibiting sales of container sizes holding less than 15 lb (6.8 kilograms) of 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane, but this restriction applied only when the chemical was intended to be a refrigerant.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] However, the ban was lifted in Wisconsin in 2012.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] During the time that it was active, this Wisconsin-specific ban contained loopholes.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] For example, it was legal for a person to purchase gas duster containers with any amount of the chemical because in that instance the chemical is neither intended to be a refrigerant nor is HFC-134a included in the § 7671a listing of class I and class II substances.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Mixtures with air of the gas 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane are not flammable at atmospheric pressure and temperatures up to 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] However, mixtures with high concentrations of air at elevated pressure and/or temperature can be ignited.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Contact of 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane with flames or hot surfaces in excess of 250 °C (482 °F) may cause vapor decomposition and the emission of toxic gases including hydrogen fluoride and carbonyl fluoride, however the decomposition temperature has been reported as above 370 °C.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] 1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane itself has an LD50 of 1,500 g/m3 in rats, making it relatively non-toxic, apart from the dangers inherent to inhalant abuse.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Its gaseous form will displace air in the lungs.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] This can result in asphyxiation if excessively inhaled.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] This contributes to most deaths by inhalant abuse.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Aerosol cans containing 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane, when inverted, become effective freeze sprays.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] Under pressure, 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane is compressed into a liquid, which upon vaporization absorbs a significant amount of thermal energy.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] As a result, it will greatly lower the temperature of any object it contacts as it evaporates.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] For its medical uses, 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane has the generic name norflurane.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It is used as propellant for some metered dose inhalers.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] In combination with pentafluoropropane, it is used as a topical vapocoolant spray for numbing boils before curettage.
[src:propane/1-1-1-2-tetrafluoroethane] It has also been studied as a potential inhalational anesthetic, but it is nonanaesthetic at doses used in inhalers.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was first reported by Henri Victor Regnault in 1840.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Industrially, it is usually produced in a two-step process from vinyl chloride.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction is catalyzed by a variety of Lewis acids, mainly aluminium chloride, iron(III) chloride, or zinc chloride.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction proceeds at 80%–90% yield, and the hydrogen chloride byproduct can be recycled to the first step in the process.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The major side-product is the related compound 1,1,2-trichloroethane, from which the 1,1,1-trichloroethane can be separated by distillation.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is sold with stabilizers because it is unstable with respect to dehydrochlorination and attacks some metals.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Stabilizers comprise up to 8% of the formulation, including acid scavengers (epoxides, amines) and complexants.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] One discontinued product contained only 1,4-dioxane (2%±1%), while another chemical supplier included 2.5% 1,4-dioxane, 0.47% 1,2-butylene oxide, and 0.35% nitromethane as stabilizers.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is an excellent solvent for many organic compounds and one of the least toxic of the chlorinated hydrocarbons.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is generally considered non-polar, but owing to the good polarizability of the chlorine atoms, it is a superior solvent for organic compounds that do not dissolve well in hydrocarbons such as hexane.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Prior to the Montreal Protocol, it was widely used for cleaning metal parts and circuit boards, as a photoresist solvent in the electronics industry, as an aerosol propellant, as a cutting fluid additive, and as a solvent for inks, paints, adhesives, and other coatings.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used to dry-clean leather and suede.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Use in dry-cleaning remained until the 1980s.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used as an insecticidal fumigant.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also the standard cleaner for photographic film.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Other commonly available solvents damage emulsion and base (acetone will dissolve triacetate base on most films), and thus are not suitable for this application.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The standard replacement, Forane 141 is much less effective, and tends to leave a residue.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also used as a thinner in correction fluid products such as liquid paper.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Many of its applications previously used carbon tetrachloride (which was banned in US consumer products in 1970).
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In turn, 1,1,1-trichloroethane itself is now being replaced by other solvents in the laboratory.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Phase-out of 1,1,1-Trichloroethane due to ozone depletion lead to a resurgence of the use of trichloroethylene in metal degreasing.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Methyl chloroform was also used as a veterinary anthelmintic.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was one of the volatile organochlorides that have been tried as alternatives to chloroform in anaesthesia.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In the 1880s, it was found to be a safe and strong substitute for chloroform but its production was too expensive and difficult for the era.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In 1880, 1,1,1-trichloroethane was suggested as an anaesthetic.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was first referred to as methyl-chloroform in the same year.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] At the time, the narcotic effects of chloral hydrate were owed to a hypothetical metabolic pathway to chloroform in "alkaline blood".
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Trichloroethane was studied for its structural similarity to chloral and potential anaesthetic effects.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] However, trichloroethane did not exhibit any conversion to chloroform in laboratory experiments.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The 1,1,2-Trichloroethane (vinyl trichloride) isomer, which lacked a trichloromethyl group, exhibited anaesthetic effects even stronger than the 1,1,1 isomer.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The International Agency for Research on Cancer places 1,1,1-trichloroethane in Group 2A as a probable carcinogen.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is a fairly potent greenhouse gas with a 100-year global warming potential of 169 relative to carbon dioxide.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This is nonetheless less than a tenth that of carbon tetrachloride — which it replaced as a solvent — due to its relatively short atmospheric lifetime of about 5 years.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The Montreal Protocol targeted 1,1,1-trichloroethane as a compound responsible for ozone depletion and banned its use beginning in 1996.
[src:propane/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Since then, its manufacture and use have been phased out throughout most of the world, and its atmospheric concentration has declined substantially.
[src:propane/1-butanol] 1-Butanol occurs naturally as a minor product of the ethanol fermentation of sugars and other saccharides and is present in many foods and drinks.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is also a permitted artificial flavorant in the United States, used in butter, cream, fruit, rum, whiskey, ice cream and ices, candy, baked goods, and cordials.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is also used in a wide range of consumer products.
[src:propane/1-butanol] The largest use of 1-butanol is as an industrial intermediate, particularly for the manufacture of butyl acetate (itself an artificial flavorant and industrial solvent).
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is a petrochemical derived from propylene.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Estimated production figures for 1997 are: United States 784,000 tonnes; Western Europe 575,000 tonnes; Japan 225,000 tonnes.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Since the 1950s, most 1-butanol is produced by the hydroformylation of propene (oxo process) to preferentially form the butyraldehyde n-butanal.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Typical catalysts are based on cobalt and rhodium.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butyraldehyde is then hydrogenated to produce butanol.
[src:propane/1-butanol] In former times, butanol was prepared from crotonaldehyde, which can be obtained from acetaldehyde.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butanol can also be produced by fermentation of biomass by bacteria.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Prior to the 1950s, *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was used in industrial fermentation to produce butanol.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Research in the past few decades showed results of other microorganisms that can produce butanol through fermentation.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butanol can be produced via furan hydrogenation over Pd or Pt catalyst at high temperature and high pressure.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Constituting 85% of its use, 1-butanol is mainly used in the production of varnishes.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is a popular solvent, e.g. for nitrocellulose.
[src:propane/1-butanol] A variety of butanol derivatives are used as solvents, e.g. butoxyethanol or butyl acetate.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Many plasticizers are based on butyl esters, e.g., dibutyl phthalate.
[src:propane/1-butanol] The monomer butyl acrylate is used to produce polymers.
[src:propane/1-butanol] 1-Butanol has been proposed as a substitute for diesel fuel and gasoline.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is produced in small quantities in nearly all fermentations (see fusel oil).
[src:propane/1-butanol] Clostridium produces much higher yields of butanol.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Research is underway to increase the biobutanol yield from biomass.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butanol is considered as a potential biofuel (butanol fuel).
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butanol at 85 percent strength can be used in cars designed for gasoline without any change to the engine (unlike 85% ethanol), and it provides more energy for a given volume than ethanol, almost as much as gasoline.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Therefore, a vehicle using butanol would return fuel consumption more comparable to gasoline than ethanol.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butanol can also be added to diesel fuel to reduce soot emissions.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol occurs naturally as a result of carbohydrate fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages, including beer, grape brandies, wine, and whisky.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It has been detected in the volatiles of hops, jack fruit, heat-treated milks, musk melon, cheese, southern pea seed, and cooked rice.
[src:propane/1-butanol] 1-Butanol is also formed during deep frying of corn oil, cottonseed oil, trilinolein, and triolein.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol is one of the "fusel alcohols" (from the German for "bad liquor"), which include alcohols that have more than two carbon atoms and have significant solubility in water.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is a natural component of many alcoholic beverages, albeit in low and variable concentrations.
[src:propane/1-butanol] It (along with similar fusel alcohols) is reputed to be responsible for severe hangovers, although experiments in animal models show no evidence for this.
[src:propane/1-butanol] The acute toxicity of 1-butanol is relatively low, with oral LD50 values of 790–4,360 mg/kg (rat; comparable values for ethanol are 7,000–15,000 mg/kg).
[src:propane/1-butanol] It is metabolized completely in vertebrates in a manner similar to ethanol: alcohol dehydrogenase converts 1-butanol to butyraldehyde; this is then converted to butyric acid by aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Butyric acid can be fully metabolized to carbon dioxide and water by the β-oxidation pathway.
[src:propane/1-butanol] In the rat, only 0.03% of an oral dose of 2,000 mg/kg was excreted in the urine.
[src:propane/1-butanol] At sub-lethal doses, 1-butanol acts as a depressant of the central nervous system, similar to ethanol: one study in rats indicated that the intoxicating potency of 1-butanol is about 6 times higher than that of ethanol, possibly because of its slower transformation by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Liquid 1-butanol, as is common with most organic solvents, is extremely irritating to the eyes; repeated contact with the skin can also cause irritation.
[src:propane/1-butanol] This is believed to be a generic effect of defatting.
[src:propane/1-butanol] No skin sensitization has been observed.
[src:propane/1-butanol] Irritation of the respiratory pathways occurs only at very high concentrations (>2,400 ppm).
[src:propane/1-butanol] With a flash point of 35 °C, 1-butanol presents a moderate fire hazard: it is slightly more flammable than kerosene or diesel fuel but less flammable than many other common organic solvents.
[src:propane/1-butanol] The depressant effect on the central nervous system (similar to ethanol intoxication) is a potential hazard when working with 1-butanol in enclosed spaces, although the odour threshold (0.2–30 ppm) is far below the concentration which would have any neurological effect.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] 1-Pentanol is prepared from 1-butene by hydroformylation followed by hydrogenation of the resulting pentanal.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] Pentanol can be prepared by fractional distillation of fusel oil.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] To reduce the use of fossil fuels, research is underway to develop cost-effective methods of producing (chemically identical) bio-pentanol with fermentation.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] The hydroxyl group (OH) is the active site of many reactions.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] The ester formed from 1-pentanol and butyric acid is pentyl butyrate, which has an apricot-like odor.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] The ester formed from 1-pentanol and acetic acid is amyl acetate (also called pentyl acetate), which has a banana-like odor.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] It is a precursor to dipentyl zinc dithiophosphates, which are used in froth flotation.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] In 2014, a study was conducted comparing the performance of diesel fuel blends with various proportions of pentanol as an additive.
[src:propane/1-pentanol] While gaseous emissions increased with higher concentrations of pentanol, particulate emissions decreased.
[src:propane/1-propanol] The compound was discovered by Gustave Chancel in 1853 by fractional distillation of fusel oil.
[src:propane/1-propanol] He measured its boiling point at 96°C, correctly identified its empirical formula, studied some of its chemical properties and gave it two names: **propionic alcohol** and **hydrate of trityl**.
[src:propane/1-propanol] After several unsuccessful attempts, it was synthesized independently and by two different routes by Eduard Linnemann and Carl Schorlemmer in 1868.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Fusel alcohols like 1-Propanol are grain fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of 1-Propanol are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:propane/1-propanol] 1-Propanol shows the normal reactions of a primary alcohol.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Thus it can be converted to alkyl halides; for example red phosphorus and iodine produce n-propyl iodide in 80% yield, while PCl3 with catalytic ZnCl2 gives n-propyl chloride.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Reaction with acetic acid in the presence of an H2SO4 catalyst under Fischer esterification conditions gives propyl acetate, while refluxing propanol overnight with formic acid alone can produce propyl formate in 65% yield.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Oxidation of 1-propanol with Na2Cr2O7 and H2SO4 gives a 36% yield of propionaldehyde, and therefore for this type of reaction higher yielding methods using PCC or the Swern oxidation are recommended.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Oxidation with chromic acid yields propionic acid.
[src:propane/1-propanol] 1-Propanol is manufactured by catalytic hydrogenation of propionaldehyde.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Propionaldehyde is produced via the oxo process by hydroformylation of ethylene using carbon monoxide and hydrogen in the presence of a catalyst such as cobalt octacarbonyl or a rhodium complex.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Other proposed industrial processes include the two-step isomerization and hydrogenation of propylene oxide.
[src:propane/1-propanol] A traditional laboratory preparation of 1-propanol involves treating *n*-propyl iodide with moist Ag2O.
[src:propane/1-propanol] 1-Propanol can also be prepared via the hydrogenation of acrolein with metal catalysts.
[src:propane/1-propanol] 1-Propanol is thought to be similar to ethanol in its effects on the human body, but 2 to 4 times more potent according to a study conducted on rabbits.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Many toxicology studies find oral acute LD50 ranging from 1.9 g/kg to 6.5 g/kg (compared to 7.06 g/kg for ethanol).
[src:propane/1-propanol] Effects include alcoholic intoxication and high anion gap metabolic acidosis.
[src:propane/1-propanol] As of 2011, one case of lethal poisoning was reported following oral ingestion of 500mL of 1-propanol.
[src:propane/1-propanol] Due to a lack of long term data, the carcinogenicity of 1-propanol in humans is unknown.
[src:propane/1-propanol] 1-Propanol has a high octane number and is suitable for use as engine fuel.
[src:propane/1-propanol] However, propanol is too expensive to use as a motor fuel.
[src:propane/1-propanol] The research octane number (RON) of propanol is 118, and the anti-knock index (AKI) is 108.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] In organic chemistry, **3-hydroxybutanal** (**acetaldol**, **aldol**) is an organic compound with the formula CH3CH(OH)CH2CHO and the structure H3C−CH(OH)−CH2−CH=O.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] It is classified as an aldol (R−CH(OH)−CHR'−C(=O)−R") and the word "aldol" can refer specifically to 3-hydroxybutanal.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] It is formally the product of the dimerization of acetaldehyde (CH3CHO).
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] A thick colorless or pale-yellow liquid, it is a versatile and valuable intermediate with diverse impacts.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] The compound is chiral although this aspect is not often exploited.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] This is the prototypical aldol reaction.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] Dehydration of 3-hydroxybutanal gives crotonaldehyde.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] This diol is a precursor to 1,3-butadiene, precursor to diverse polymers.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] Polymerization of 3-hydroxybutanal is also spontaneous, but can be stopped with the addition of water.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] Aldol has been used in making perfumes and in ore flotation.
[src:propane/3-hydroxybutanal] It was formerly used in medicine as a hypnotic and sedative.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Diberal, unlike most barbiturates, can have convulsant actions.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] This is uncommon, as barbiturates typically enhance the function of GABA as allorestic modulators and agonists (at higher doses), therefore having anticonvulsant properties.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Depending on which isomer is used, it can have either convulsant or anticonvulsant actions.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] The different pharmacological profile between isomers is thought to be due to the differences in the formation of hydrogen bonds at the binding sites.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (+)-DMBB is the atypical enantiomer of diberal.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It is atypical in the means that it has convulsant action, unlike most barbiturate drugs.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Unlike (+)-DMBB, the (−)-isomer is similar to most barbiturates by having anticonvulsant action.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It has been found that administration of (−)-DMBB reverses the convulsant actions of (+)-DMBB.
[src:propane/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (−)-DMBB is slightly more potent than pentobarbital in its depressant properties.
[src:propane/propane] Propane gas has become a popular choice for barbecues and portable stoves because its low −42 °C boiling point makes it vaporise inside pressurised liquid containers (it exists in two phases, vapor above liquid).
[src:propane/propane] It retains its ability to vaporise even in cold weather, making it better-suited for outdoor use in cold climates than alternatives with higher boiling points like butane.
[src:propane/propane] LPG powers buses, forklifts, automobiles, outboard boat motors, and ice resurfacing machines, and is used for heat and cooking in recreational vehicles and campers.
[src:propane/propane] Propane is also becoming popular as a replacement refrigerant (R290) for heat pumps as it offers greater efficiency than the current refrigerants: R410A / R32, higher temperature heat output and less damage to the atmosphere for escaped gases—at the expense of high gas flammability.
[src:propane/propane] Propane was first synthesized by the French chemist Marcellin Berthelot in 1857 during his researches on hydrogenation.
[src:propane/propane] Berthelot made propane by heating propylene dibromide (C3H6Br2) with potassium iodide and water.
[src:propane/propane] Propane was found dissolved in Pennsylvanian light crude oil by Edmund Ronalds in 1864.
[src:propane/propane] Bureau of Mines highlighted it as a volatile component in gasoline in 1910, which marked the "birth of the propane industry" in the United States.
[src:propane/propane] The volatility of these lighter hydrocarbons caused them to be known as "wild" because of the high vapor pressures of unrefined gasoline.
[src:propane/propane] On March 31, 1912, *The New York Times* reported on Snelling's work with liquefied gas, saying "a steel bottle will carry enough gas to light an ordinary home for three weeks".
[src:propane/propane] It was during this time that Snelling*—*in cooperation with Frank P.
[src:propane/propane] Peterson, Chester Kerr, and Arthur Kerr*—*developed ways to liquefy the LP gases during the refining of gasoline.
[src:propane/propane] Together, they established American Gasol Co., the first commercial marketer of propane.
[src:propane/propane] Snelling had produced relatively pure propane by 1911, and on March 25, 1913, his method of processing and producing LP gases was issued patent #1,056,845.
[src:propane/propane] A separate method of producing LP gas through compression was developed by Frank Peterson and its patent was granted on July 2, 1912.
[src:propane/propane] The 1920s saw increased production of LP gases, with the first year of recorded production totaling 223,000 US gallons (840 m3) in 1922.
[src:propane/propane] In 1927, annual marketed LP gas production reached 1 million US gallons (3,800 m3), and by 1935, the annual sales of LP gas had reached 56 million US gallons (210,000 m3).
[src:propane/propane] Major industry developments in the 1930s included the introduction of railroad tank car transport, gas odorization, and the construction of local bottle-filling plants.
[src:propane/propane] The year 1945 marked the first year that annual LP gas sales reached a billion gallons.
[src:propane/propane] By 1947, 62% of all U.S. homes had been equipped with either natural gas or propane for cooking.
[src:propane/propane] In 1950, 1,000 propane-fueled buses were ordered by the Chicago Transit Authority, and by 1958, sales in the U.S. had reached 7 billion US gallons (26,000,000 m3) annually.
[src:propane/propane] In 2004, it was reported to be a growing $8-billion to $10-billion industry with over 15 billion US gallons (57,000,000 m3) of propane being used annually in the U.S.
[src:propane/propane] During the COVID-19 pandemic, propane shortages were reported in the United States due to increased demand.
[src:propane/propane] The *prop-* root found in *propane* and names of other compounds with three-carbon chains was derived from *propionic acid*, which in turn was derived from the Ancient Greek words πρῶτος, *protos*, "first" and πίων, *pion*, "fat", as it was the "first" member of the series of fatty acids.
[src:propane/propane] Ethyl mercaptan is added as a safety precaution as an odorizer, and is commonly called a "rotten egg" smell.
[src:propane/propane] At normal pressure it liquifies below its boiling point at −42 °C and solidifies below its melting point at −187.7 °C.
[src:propane/propane] Propane crystallizes in the space group P21/n.
[src:propane/propane] The low space-filling of 58.5% (at 90 K), due to the bad stacking properties of the molecule, is the reason for the particularly low melting point.
[src:propane/propane] Propane undergoes combustion reactions in a similar fashion to other alkanes.
[src:propane/propane] Propane combustion is much cleaner than that of coal or unleaded gasoline.
[src:propane/propane] Propane's per-BTU production of CO2 is almost as low as that of natural gas.
[src:propane/propane] Propane burns hotter than home heating oil or diesel fuel because of the very high hydrogen content.
[src:propane/propane] The presence of C–C bonds, plus the multiple bonds of propylene and butylene, produce organic exhausts besides carbon dioxide and water vapor during typical combustion.
[src:propane/propane] These bonds also cause propane to burn with a visible flame.
[src:propane/propane] The enthalpy of combustion of propane gas where all products return to standard state, for example where water returns to its liquid state at standard temperature (known as higher heating value), is (2,219.2 ± 0.5) kJ/mol, or (50.33 ± 0.01) MJ/kg.
[src:propane/propane] The enthalpy of combustion of propane gas where products do not return to standard state, for example where the hot gases including water vapor exit a chimney, (known as lower heating value) is 2,043.455 kJ/mol.
[src:propane/propane] The lower heat value is the amount of heat available from burning the substance where the combustion products are vented to the atmosphere; for example, the heat from a fireplace when the flue is open.
[src:propane/propane] The density of propane gas at 25 °C (77 °F) is 1.808 kg/m3, about 1.5× the density of air at the same temperature.
[src:propane/propane] The density of liquid propane at 25 °C (77 °F) is 0.493 g/cm3, which is equivalent to 4.11 pounds per U.S. liquid gallon or 493 g/L.
[src:propane/propane] Thus, liquid propane has a density of approximately 4.2 pounds per gallon (504 g/L) at 60 °F (15.6 °C).
[src:propane/propane] As the density of propane changes with temperature, this fact must be considered every time when the application is connected with safety or custody transfer operations.
[src:propane/propane] If enough headspace is not left in a tank when filling, the tank could rupture when it heats up.
[src:propane/propane] Propane is a popular choice for barbecues and portable stoves because the low boiling point of −42 °C (−44 °F) makes it vaporize as soon as it is released from its pressurized container.
[src:propane/propane] Therefore, no carburetor or other vaporizing device is required; a simple metering nozzle suffices.
[src:propane/propane] Blends of pure, dry "isopropane" [isobutane/propane mixtures of propane (R-290) and isobutane (R-600a)] can be used as the circulating refrigerant in suitably constructed compressor-based refrigeration.
[src:propane/propane] Because its global warming effect is far less than current refrigerants, propane was chosen as one of five replacement refrigerants approved by the EPA in 2015, for use in systems specially designed to handle its flammability.
[src:propane/propane] Such substitution is widely prohibited or discouraged in motor vehicle air conditioning systems, on the grounds that using flammable hydrocarbons in systems originally designed to carry non-flammable refrigerant presents a significant risk of fire or explosion.
[src:propane/propane] Vendors and advocates of hydrocarbon refrigerants argue against such bans on the grounds that there have been very few such incidents relative to the number of vehicle air conditioning systems filled with hydrocarbons.
[src:propane/propane] Propane is also instrumental in providing off-the-grid refrigeration, as the energy source for a gas absorption refrigerator, and is commonly used for camping and recreational vehicles.
[src:propane/propane] It has also been proposed to use propane as a refrigerant in heat pumps.
[src:propane/propane] Since it can be transported easily, it is a popular fuel for home heat and backup electrical generation in sparsely populated areas that do not have natural gas pipelines.
[src:propane/propane] In June 2023, Stanford University researchers found propane combustion emitted detectable and repeatable levels of benzene that in some homes raised indoor benzene concentrations above well-established health benchmarks.
[src:propane/propane] The research also shows that gas and propane fuels appear to be the dominant source of benzene produced by cooking.
[src:propane/propane] In rural areas of North America, as well as northern Australia, propane is used to heat livestock facilities, in grain dryers, and other heat-producing appliances.
[src:propane/propane] When used for heating or grain drying it is usually stored in a large, permanently-placed cylinder which is refilled by a propane-delivery truck.
[src:propane/propane] As of 2014, 6.2 million American households use propane as their primary heating fuel.
[src:propane/propane] In North America, local delivery trucks with an average cylinder size of 3,000 US gallons (11 m3), fill up large cylinders that are permanently installed on the property, or other service trucks exchange empty cylinders of propane with filled cylinders.
[src:propane/propane] Large tractor-trailer trucks, with an average cylinder size of 10,000 US gallons (38 m3), transport propane from the pipeline or refinery to the local bulk plant.
[src:propane/propane] The bobtail tank truck is not unique to the North American market, though the practice is not as common elsewhere, and the vehicles are generally called *tankers*.
[src:propane/propane] In many countries, propane is delivered to end-users via small or medium-sized individual cylinders, while empty cylinders are removed for refilling at a central location.
[src:propane/propane] There are also community propane systems, with a central cylinder feeding individual homes.
[src:propane/propane] In the U.S., over 190,000 on-road vehicles use propane, and over 450,000 forklifts use it for power.
[src:propane/propane] It is the third most popular vehicle fuel in the world, behind gasoline and diesel fuel.
[src:propane/propane] In other parts of the world, propane used in vehicles is known as *autogas*.
[src:propane/propane] In 2007, approximately 13 million vehicles worldwide use autogas.
[src:propane/propane] The advantage of propane in cars is its liquid state at a moderate pressure.
[src:propane/propane] This allows fast refill times, affordable fuel cylinder construction, and price ranges typically just over half that of gasoline.
[src:propane/propane] Meanwhile, it is noticeably cleaner (both in handling, and in combustion), results in less engine wear (due to carbon deposits) without diluting engine oil (often extending oil-change intervals), and until recently was relatively low-cost in North America.
[src:propane/propane] The octane rating of propane is relatively high at 110.
[src:propane/propane] In the United States the propane fueling infrastructure is the most developed of all alternative vehicle fuels.
[src:propane/propane] Many converted vehicles have provisions for topping off from "barbecue bottles".
[src:propane/propane] Purpose-built vehicles are often in commercially owned fleets with private fueling facilities.
[src:propane/propane] A further saving for propane fuel vehicle operators, especially in fleets, is that theft is much more difficult than with gasoline or diesel fuels.
[src:propane/propane] Propane is also used as fuel for small engines, especially those used indoors or in areas with insufficient fresh air and ventilation to carry away the more toxic exhaust of an engine running on gasoline or diesel fuel.
[src:propane/propane] More recently, there have been lawn-care products like string trimmers, lawn mowers and leaf blowers intended for outdoor use, but fueled by propane in order to reduce air pollution.
[src:propane/propane] Many heavy-duty highway trucks use propane as a boost, where it is added through the turbocharger, to mix with diesel fuel droplets.
[src:propane/propane] The very high hydrogen content of propane helps the diesel fuel to burn hotter and therefore more completely.
[src:propane/propane] This provides more torque, more horsepower, and a cleaner exhaust for the trucks.
[src:propane/propane] It is normal for a 7-liter medium-duty diesel truck engine to increase fuel economy by 20 to 33 percent when a propane boost system is used.
[src:propane/propane] It is cheaper because propane is much cheaper than diesel fuel.
[src:propane/propane] The longer distance a cross-country trucker can travel on a full load of combined diesel and propane fuel means they can maintain federal hours of work rules with two fewer fuel stops in a cross-country trip.
[src:propane/propane] Truckers, tractor pulling competitions, and farmers have been using a propane boost system for over forty years in North America.
[src:propane/propane] The North American standard grade of automotive-use propane is rated HD-5 (Heavy Duty 5%).
[src:propane/propane] HD-5 grade has a maximum of 5 percent butane, but propane sold in Europe has a maximum allowable amount of butane of 30 percent, meaning it is not the same fuel as HD-5.
[src:propane/propane] The LPG used as auto fuel and cooking gas in Asia and Australia also has very high butane content.
[src:propane/propane] Propylene (also called propene) can be a contaminant of commercial propane.
[src:propane/propane] Propane containing too much propene is not suited for most vehicle fuels.
[src:propane/propane] HD-5 is a specification that establishes a maximum concentration of 5% propene in propane.
[src:propane/propane] Propane and other LP gas specifications are established in ASTM D-1835.
[src:propane/propane] All propane fuels include an odorant, almost always ethanethiol, so that the gas can be smelled easily in case of a leak.
[src:propane/propane] Propane as HD-5 was originally intended for use as vehicle fuel.
[src:propane/propane] HD-5 is currently being used in all propane applications.
[src:propane/propane] Typically in the United States and Canada, LPG is primarily propane (at least 90%), while the rest is mostly ethane, propylene, butane, and odorants including ethyl mercaptan.
[src:propane/propane] This is the HD-5 standard, (maximum allowable propylene content, and no more than 5% butanes and ethane) defined by the American Society for Testing and Materials by its Standard 1835 for internal combustion engines.
[src:propane/propane] Not all products labeled "LPG" conform to this standard, however.
[src:propane/propane] In Mexico, for example, gas labeled "LPG" may consist of 60% propane and 40% butane.
[src:propane/propane] "The exact proportion of this combination varies by country, depending on international prices, on the availability of components and, especially, on the climatic conditions that favor LPG with higher butane content in warmer regions and propane in cold areas".
[src:propane/propane] Propane is bought and stored in a liquid form, LPG.
[src:propane/propane] It can easily be stored in a relatively small space.
[src:propane/propane] By comparison, compressed natural gas (CNG) cannot be liquefied by compression at normal temperatures, as these are well above its critical temperature.
[src:propane/propane] As a gas, very high pressure is required to store useful quantities.
[src:propane/propane] This poses the hazard that, in an accident, just as with any compressed gas cylinder (such as a CO2 cylinder used for a soda concession) a CNG cylinder may burst with great force, or leak rapidly enough to become a self-propelled missile.
[src:propane/propane] Therefore, CNG is much less efficient to store than propane, due to the large cylinder volume required.
[src:propane/propane] An alternative means of storing natural gas is as a cryogenic liquid in an insulated container as liquefied natural gas (LNG).
[src:propane/propane] This form of storage is at low pressure and is around 3.5 times as efficient as storing it as CNG.
[src:propane/propane] Unlike propane, if a spill occurs, CNG will evaporate and dissipate because it is lighter than air.
[src:propane/propane] Propane is much more commonly used to fuel vehicles than is natural gas, because that equipment costs less.
[src:propane/propane] Propane requires just 1,220 kilopascals (177 psi) of pressure to keep it liquid at 37.8 °C (100 °F).
[src:propane/propane] Unlike natural gas, it is denser than air.
[src:propane/propane] It may accumulate in low spaces and near the floor.
[src:propane/propane] When abused as an inhalant, it may cause hypoxia (lack of oxygen), pneumonia, cardiac failure or cardiac arrest.
[src:propane/propane] Propane has low toxicity since it is not readily absorbed and is not biologically active.
[src:propane/propane] Commonly stored under pressure at room temperature, propane and its mixtures will flash evaporate at atmospheric pressure and cool well below the freezing point of water.
[src:propane/propane] The cold gas, which appears white due to moisture condensing from the air, may cause frostbite.
[src:propane/propane] If a leak in a propane fuel system occurs, the vaporized gas will have a tendency to sink into any enclosed area and thus poses a risk of explosion and fire.
[src:propane/propane] The typical scenario is a leaking cylinder stored in a basement; the propane leak drifts across the floor to the pilot light on the furnace or water heater, and results in an explosion or fire.
[src:propane/propane] This property makes propane generally unsuitable as a fuel for boats.
[src:propane/propane] In 2007, a heavily investigated vapor-related explosion occurred in Ghent, West Virginia, U.S., killing four people and completely destroying the Little General convenience store on Flat Top Road, causing several injuries.
[src:propane/propane] Another hazard associated with propane storage and transport is known as a BLEVE or boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion.
[src:propane/propane] The Kingman Explosion involved a railroad tank car in Kingman, Arizona, U.S., in 1973 during a propane transfer.
[src:propane/propane] The fire and subsequent explosions resulted in twelve fatalities and numerous injuries.
[src:propane/propane] Propane is produced as a by-product of two other processes, natural gas processing and petroleum refining.
[src:propane/propane] The processing of natural gas involves removal of butane, propane, and large amounts of ethane from the raw gas, to prevent condensation of these volatiles in natural gas pipelines.
[src:propane/propane] Additionally, oil refineries produce some propane as a by-product of cracking petroleum into gasoline or heating oil.
[src:propane/propane] The supply of propane cannot easily be adjusted to meet increased demand, because of the by-product nature of propane production.
[src:propane/propane] About 90% of U.S. propane is domestically produced.
[src:propane/propane] The United States imports about 10% of the propane consumed each year, with about 70% of that coming from Canada via pipeline and rail.
[src:propane/propane] The remaining 30% of imported propane comes to the United States from other sources via ocean transport.
[src:propane/propane] After it is separated from the crude oil, North American propane is stored in huge salt caverns.
[src:propane/propane] Examples of these are Fort Saskatchewan, Alberta; Mont Belvieu, Texas; and Conway, Kansas.
[src:propane/propane] As of October 2013, the retail cost of propane was approximately $2.37 per gallon, or roughly $25.95 per 1 million BTUs.
[src:propane/propane] This means that filling a 500-gallon propane tank, which is what households that use propane as their main source of energy usually require, cost $948 (80% of 500 gallons or 400 gallons), a 7.5% increase on the 2012–2013 winter season average US price.
[src:propane/propane] However, propane costs per gallon change significantly from one state to another: the Energy Information Administration (EIA) quotes a $2.995 per gallon average on the East Coast for October 2013, while the figure for the Midwest was $1.860 for the same period.
[src:propane/propane] As of December 2015, the propane retail cost was approximately $1.97 per gallon, which meant filling a 500-gallon propane tank to 80% capacity cost $788, a 16.9% decrease or $160 less from November 2013.
[src:propane/propane] Similar regional differences in prices are present with the December 2015 EIA figure for the East Coast at $2.67 per gallon and the Midwest at $1.43 per gallon.
[src:propane/propane] As of August 2018, the average US propane retail cost was approximately $2.48 per gallon.
[src:propane/propane] The wholesale price of propane in the U.S. always drops in the summer as most homes do not require it for home heating.
[src:propane/propane] The wholesale price of propane in the summer of 2018 was between 86 cents to 96 cents per U.S. gallon, based on a truckload or railway car load.
[src:propane/propane] The price for home heating was exactly double that price; at 95 cents per gallon wholesale, a home-delivered price was $1.90 per gallon if ordered 500 gallons at a time.
[src:propane/propane] Prices for home delivery always go up near the end of August or the first few days of September when people start ordering their home tanks to be filled.
[src:propane/propane] Propane was first discovered in space in 1981 in the atmosphere of Saturn's moon Titan based on spectroscopic observations from the Voyager 1 IRIS instrument.
[src:propane/propane] This was subsequently confirmed by ground-based observations using the TEXES instrument on the IRTF telescope and mapped by the CIRS instrument on Cassini.
[src:propane/propane] Propane was subsequently been detected in the atmosphere of Saturn using TEXES, and predicted but unconfirmed on Jupiter, Neptune and Uranus.
